




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Understanding Predictability
AU  - Menzly, Lior
AU  - Santos, Tano
AU  - Veronesi, Pietro
Y1  - 2004/02/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/379934
DO  - 10.1086/379934
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1
EP  - 47
VL  - 112
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We propose a general equilibrium model with multiple securities in which investors? risk preferences and expectations of dividend growth are time?varying. While time?varying risk preferences induce the standard positive relation between the dividend yield and expected returns, time?varying expected dividend growth induces a negative relation between them. These offsetting effects reduce the ability of the dividend yield to forecast returns and eliminate its ability to forecast dividend growth, as observed in the data. The model links the predictability of returns to that of dividend growth, suggesting specific changes to standard linear predictive regressions for both. The model?s predictions are confirmed empirically.
AB  - We propose a general equilibrium model with multiple securities in which investors? risk preferences and expectations of dividend growth are time?varying. While time?varying risk preferences induce the standard positive relation between the dividend yield and expected returns, time?varying expected dividend growth induces a negative relation between them. These offsetting effects reduce the ability of the dividend yield to forecast returns and eliminate its ability to forecast dividend growth, as observed in the data. The model links the predictability of returns to that of dividend growth, suggesting specific changes to standard linear predictive regressions for both. The model?s predictions are confirmed empirically.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/379934
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/379934
Y2  - 2024/03/19
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Direct Test of the Theory of Comparative Advantage: The Case of Japan
AU  - Bernhofen, Daniel M.
AU  - Brown, John C.
Y1  - 2004/02/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/379944
DO  - 10.1086/379944
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 48
EP  - 67
VL  - 112
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We exploit Japan?s sudden and complete opening up to international trade in the 1860s to test the empirical validity of one of the oldest and most fundamental propositions in economics: the theory of comparative advantage. Historical evidence supports the assertion that the characteristics of the Japanese economy at the time were compatible with the key assumptions of the neoclassical trade model. Using detailed product?specific data on autarky prices and trade flows, we find that the autarky price value of Japan?s trade is negative for each year of the period 1868?75. This confirms the prediction of the theory.
AB  - We exploit Japan?s sudden and complete opening up to international trade in the 1860s to test the empirical validity of one of the oldest and most fundamental propositions in economics: the theory of comparative advantage. Historical evidence supports the assertion that the characteristics of the Japanese economy at the time were compatible with the key assumptions of the neoclassical trade model. Using detailed product?specific data on autarky prices and trade flows, we find that the autarky price value of Japan?s trade is negative for each year of the period 1868?75. This confirms the prediction of the theory.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/379944
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/379944
Y2  - 2024/03/19
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Differentiated Products Demand Systems from a Combination of Micro and Macro Data: The New Car Market
AU  - Berry, Steven
AU  - Levinsohn, James
AU  - Pakes, Ariel
Y1  - 2004/02/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/379939
DO  - 10.1086/379939
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 68
EP  - 105
VL  - 112
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In this paper, we consider how rich sources of information on consumer choice can help to identify demand parameters in a widely used class of differentiated products demand models. Most important, we show how to use ?second?choice? data on automotive purchases to obtain good estimates of substitution patterns in the automobile industry. We use our estimates to make out?of?sample predictions about important recent changes in industry structure.
AB  - In this paper, we consider how rich sources of information on consumer choice can help to identify demand parameters in a widely used class of differentiated products demand models. Most important, we show how to use ?second?choice? data on automotive purchases to obtain good estimates of substitution patterns in the automobile industry. We use our estimates to make out?of?sample predictions about important recent changes in industry structure.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/379939
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/379939
Y2  - 2024/03/19
